A thorough introduction to the husband's character would engage you emotionally with his fate and provide insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, the depth of their bond, and hints about her thoughts and dreams reflected through his perspective, among other things. You would mourn his death with her, thus growing more connected to the heroine.

In summary, you'd expect more depth on the simple storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to add that depth. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, continues*) Sometimes, the temptation is to rush through certain elements. Maybe you're introducing a new character and know he used to be in the Air Force, is now the night manager of a gas station, was married twice, has no kids, enjoys fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was a live broadcast from NBC 4 on the morning of August 13, 2011. The main story covered a man named Shad Hostettler in Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife multiple times. Even though they didn't mention her name, they showed Hostettler's mug shot, portraying him as quite menacing. The report on this developing story lasted about two minutes, which I felt was appropriate given the circumstances. 

The second story involved an early morning shooting victim, 18-year-old Travis Buyers, who was critically injured in the Sharon Woods area. At the time, there were no arrests or suspects, and the SWAT Team was investigating. This report was brief, and I suspect that might be because the victim was a black man or from a black neighborhood. I've noticed, over the years, that crimes involving minorities often receive less media attention compared to similar incidents involving white victims. 

Another story discussed the discovery of a bullet hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details included the location of the suspected incident and that a .22 caliber rifle bullet was responsible. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for information leading to the arrest of the shooter. 

The forecast for rain and thunderstorms on Saturday afternoon was also mentioned. Temperatures were expected to stay in the mid to low 80s over the weekend. This segment was brief, likely intended as a teaser to keep viewers tuned in. 

They also reported on a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus, describing the suspect as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie, approximately six feet tall and weighing around 150 pounds. I found it odd that they emphasized the suspect's race and skin tone so much. 

Another segment covered Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin, involved in a conspiracy to distribute large amounts of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. Interestingly, instead of saying he was sentenced to 25 years in prison, they stated "300 months," which seemed to be intended to sound harsher. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which I didn't think was relevant to the story.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a type of security that aims to track the performance of an index, a commodity, or a collection of assets similar to an index fund. However, unlike index funds, ETFs offer greater flexibility as they are traded like stocks on exchanges. ETFs allow investors to enjoy the diversification benefits of an index fund while also providing the advantages of individual stock ownership, such as the ability to sell short, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share per transaction. Although these features are highly appealing, ETFs typically have much lower expense ratios compared to the average mutual fund. On the downside, trading ETFs incurs a commission fee, similar to stock trades. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide range of funds available. Despite these benefits being clearly outlined, it is wise for astute investors to assess whether the claimed benefits, such as diversification, truly exist and to what degree. For this analysis, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it to its top 10 holdings to evaluate if the advantages of owning a single ETF are comparable to possessing a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks, and whether there might be better configurations of these stocks to achieve an optimal Sharpe ratio or return.  
To assess the ETF, we will focus on the top ten holdings, which account for 63.58% of the ETF's total assets, as including every holding would be impractical. The top 10 holdings and their asset percentages are listed below.  
To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the entire ETF IHF, we can use their current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate each stock's contribution to a portfolio's Beta and Return, assuming the portfolio consists solely of these 10 stocks in the proportions set by the ETF. The Beta and return calculations are provided in the chart below.  
The chart shows that a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings yields a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, translating to a 16% increase in returns. It also shows that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than that of the entire ETF. Based on these results, a portfolio comprising just the top 10 holdings could potentially offer higher returns with a lower beta. However, it's possible that the means of these two portfolios might not differ significantly from each other statistically.  
To determine if these portfolios are statistically different, we calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their combined standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring to Figure 17, there was a sharp decline in commuter log submissions during the project's third month, which was somewhat disheartening, and the reasons for this are unclear. The arrival of winter on a New England campus likely led to fewer people commuting by bicycle or on foot, contributing to the decrease. December also signifies the end of the fall semester when everyone is preoccupied with completing schoolwork and processing grades, possibly causing the commuter log to be overlooked. Additionally, December ushers in the busy holiday season and a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to come to campus. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which might explain the low number of logs for that month. However, this doesn't fully account for the low submissions in February. It is possible that projects of this nature experience an initial surge of enthusiasm that naturally wanes over time. To counter this trend, we initiated the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a focused campaign that successfully boosted log submissions for that month. Thus, one challenge was maintaining project momentum despite a natural decline in engagement, along with the specific issue of holiday and semester breaks in higher education. 

Another challenge for this project, or any alternative commuting project, is the widespread preference for the freedom, independence, and flexibility that driving offers, which is deeply ingrained in our culture. Therefore, it is crucial to provide incentives for alternative commuting. We offered numerous prizes, such as gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see the impact of larger prizes on participation, such as a bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car, which might have helped address the dip in engagement. The nature of the prizes remained consistent throughout the project. If the prize value had increased over time, it might have helped. The gift cards seemed sufficient at the project's start, but announcing the addition of bicycles in December and a hybrid or electric car in January might have boosted participation and engagement instead of seeing a decline.

While exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I chose to watch all fifteen trick films produced between 1895 and 1901. These films typically utilize creative editing to create illusions. My film analysis primarily focused on defining the stylistic elements of most trick films and investigating the unique features found in some of the later ones. Generally, trick films from the turn of the century are confined to a set, structured within a frontal proscenium, lack camera movement, use long and medium shots, and follow the one shot = one film principle. However, a few films from the early 1900s deviate from these norms by incorporating multiple shots.

A key characteristic shared by these films is their use of an indoor set framed by a frontal proscenium. The camera remains stationary in its proscenium position, not following figures or objects. This style was prevalent in early cinema, influenced by theater and, in trick films, vaudeville and magic performances. A limitation of this stage setup is that characters in trick films generally move side-to-side, avoiding movement toward or away from the camera. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move horizontally. Even when they exit the frame, the camera remains still.

The frontal proscenium composition also results in predominantly long shots, with medium shots being less common. Close-ups are absent from any of the Edison trick films. This mirrors the theater and vaudeville tradition, where audiences view the entire performance at once, framed by the stage. In early films, actors do not approach the camera from the middle distance, so close-ups are not used.

Most early trick films adhere to the principle that one conceptual shot constitutes the entire film. This confines the duration of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frame rate. It also limits the narrative potential of the films, which mostly focus on brief vaudeville-style tricks like magic, disappearing acts, and transformations with minimal storytelling. However, in trick films, a single conceptual shot is not necessarily one physical shot. A "shot" may consist of several shots combined to create illusions of appearing or disappearing. For instance, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), a close examination shows where the physical shot starts with Mary's "head" being removed, though to the viewer, the film appears as a single conceptual shot.

Ian Watt, in "The Rise of the Gothic Novel," refers to the traditional "Gothic Novel" as an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" highlighting its contradictory nature both in substance and name. The Gothic style has faced criticism and praise alike, with some accusing it of lacking depth while others celebrate its ability to evoke the 'terrible sublime,' as noted by Burke. Horace Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto," the first "Gothic Novel," fused elements of "ancient and modern" romances to pioneer the proto-Gothic genre and develop a new literary form. Walpole incorporated "old" theatrical techniques and 'new' naturalistic imitations in 'modern' novels to craft what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre often incorporates elements from medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. At the time "The Castle of Otranto" was published, "gothic" was used to describe a variety of peoples, styles, and epochs, often seen as outdated or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The blend of theatrical "Gothic" elements with the novel's format, which provides a more intimate glimpse into character psychology, has allowed the Gothic genre to endure, appearing both outdated and novel to readers far removed in time from its original creation.

A key concept in Gothic novels is Chivalry. The medieval notion of chivalry, the training of a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in "The Castle of Otranto." Chivalry holds special significance for Gothic writers due to its representation of the quintessential knight—brave, honorable, and skilled—and the perceived absence of such ideals in society, particularly noted by Walpole. By incorporating chivalric ideals and behaviors, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, hinting at the Gothic genre's evolution towards Romanticism, and is used as a means to critique and potentially improve the present. While writing "The Castle of Otranto," Walpole was amidst political turmoil and was concerned about the future. Immersed in politics and facing possibly unjust accusations, he might have believed that the morality and inherent "goodness" of people from the gothic era had been lost in contemporary society. This idea is evident in his characters, such as Frederic, who is portrayed with many chivalric qualities. Frederic is described as a prince who has endured hardship, been affected by tragedy, and is believed to have been killed by infidels. The depiction of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management encompasses the series of processes involved in moving goods from the point of customer order through stages of raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. This concept was introduced in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver, who detailed the comprehensive process of planning, executing, and overseeing supply chain activities to meet customer needs effectively and efficiently. The supply chain is composed of six essential components: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these components to deliver optimal customer service. 

Production marks the initial phase of the supply chain process, serving as the backbone for the entire series of operations. This stage defines the timing, reasons, locations, and methods for production. Managers must understand customer preferences, which can be discerned by analyzing market trends. The market acts as a primary indicator of customer demand. Once managers understand this demand, they can determine which products to produce and in what quantities. Subsequently, they decide on the optimal production sites and facilities that will meet the required volume and quality, ensuring customer satisfaction. Following the selection of production locations, managers then concentrate on workload scheduling and equipment maintenance. Production is a crucial step within the supply chain, and every detail must be meticulously planned to avoid costly errors in time and resources over the long term. For instance, when I worked at Wal-Mart and Target retail stores, both companies had detailed guides and processes for various business aspects, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments. Such structured processes enable smooth operations and clarity in roles and expectations.

The second critical component in supply chain management is supply. Supply involves strategic decision-making to identify the essential capabilities of a facility, and it determines the development of outsourcing partnerships. A single product may have multiple production divisions, each with unique equipment, personnel, and expertise. Managers must evaluate which division best suits different product processes. Additionally, management might opt to outsource certain tasks to other companies. The primary motivation for outsourcing is to enhance velocity, which is the ability to deliver quality and flexibility while simultaneously reducing or maintaining low cost levels.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous detail and focus on the period's aristocracy. However, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, while considered Victorian, diverge from this tradition. Both novels incorporate elements of mystery and the unusual, which are not typical of the era's literature, thereby enhancing the characters and offering deeper insights into their motivations and emotions.

"Now, a torrent of bewildering and confusing thoughts surged through his mind. He felt as if he was still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were fiercely arguing; their words echoed in his ears, and he realized he was talking to them himself. Suddenly, he jolted at the sound of gunshots; cries and shouts filled the air, lights flashed before his eyes, and noise and chaos surrounded him as an unseen force whisked him away. Amidst these swift visions, he felt a vague, uneasy sense of pain that constantly wearied and tormented him." (Dickens, 220)

The two novels frequently use mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, with varying content and purpose in each case. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences often reveal insights into Oliver’s inner self, his suffering, and his awareness of the true nature of his surroundings. When the incident of Oliver being shot is revisited in chapter 28, he re-experiences the event vividly, as if in a dream, while struggling to seek help. This passage highlights Oliver's lack of control over the unfolding events and the precarious state of his health, emphasized by his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms his senses; he doesn't notice the "unseen hand" that carries him away, reliving the despair detached from the initial shock since the pain has become constant and is linked with fear rather than surprise. This overwhelming experience raises questions about who is responsible for his misfortune, as it is certainly not his own doing. The shooting underscores that Oliver has little control over anything, unable to even attempt to influence the outcome of events, even when his life is at stake. This passage implies a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as if old Fagin is beginning to break him, pushing him to accept despair and diminishing his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least to save his own life.

"The day passed – day! There was no day; it vanished as soon as it appeared – and night returned; a night so long, yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

A few years back, I was involved in an after-school program where I tutored elementary students. I aimed to assist them in any subject they found challenging, although my expertise lay in English and reading. One of the instructors asked me to help a young boy named Adrian, who was in the third or fourth grade and faced significant difficulties with reading. It struck me that there was an unusual issue; while he could pronounce some letters perfectly, others eluded him entirely. Despite his Latino heritage, Adrian spoke flawless English. We encountered several challenges until I met his mother while supervising a few students who didn’t attend a field trip. Adrian's mother spoke only Spanish, and with my limited Spanish skills, we managed to communicate. That’s when I realized Adrian's issue wasn’t reading itself but his unfamiliarity with the English alphabet. Although I'm unsure if this insight made a difference for him, I hope he is doing better now. 

I share this story to highlight the language barrier issue in schools, particularly in California, and to illustrate that it’s not always as evident as it seems. Even children who speak perfect English can face substantial challenges in reading. While I think everyone acknowledges the existence of this problem, the question remains: how do we address it? For Adrian, the solution was straightforward: English reading tutoring, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for many children who are not fluent in English, the solution is more complicated. There's no single answer. A combination of dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutors, and ESL classes is essential.

The dual language system is an excellent concept, not just for Spanish-speaking students but for all children. Studies show that children in two-way bilingual education programs often outperform their peers academically. Despite fears that such programs waste resources and offer no benefit to most students, this is untrue. If these programs were standard rather than exceptions, all students would benefit. But how do we implement this? Requiring all teachers to be bilingual is impractical. Nevertheless, there's no reason we can't employ bilingual aides or tutors.

From a young age, many of us are taught that there exists something greater than ourselves, something beyond our understanding. Some are taken to Sunday school to learn about it, others attend Temple, or look inward for answers. Many people easily embrace the religions passed down by their parents, while others completely reject them, believing there's nothing beyond their personal, self-centered world. We might adopt one belief system only to later change to another. Regardless of the path we take, we embark on a journey to define a part of ourselves through our own unique views on spirituality. We seek a guiding light in the darkness to lead us out of the shadows and into the sunshine.

"A cardinal," my father answered when I asked him about his favorite bird. We sat on our front porch, listening to the rain drumming on the tin roof overhead while we shared cigarettes. The gutters channeled the rain down, overwhelming the plants by the porch. He gazed into the rain with a look that seemed both searching and remembering. Over the past months, he had become thinner, his clothes hanging loosely on his body, and his hair had thinned more than I recalled. He continued to look into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, scared, and unable to express to my father how much I would miss him, because speaking about it would make it all too real for us both. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in watching the rain fall on that June evening.

My father passed away in December that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation did not ease his suffering but prolonged his life a few months beyond what the doctors had predicted; the value of this extension, given his continued suffering, was unclear to me. I questioned what kind of God would allow this to happen. Alone at night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I felt he had long stopped listening to me.

I couldn’t bear to watch him transition from this life to the next, so I didn’t. I couldn’t watch the life that brought me into existence come to an end. I wanted to remember my father for how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew him better than anyone else, and I knew he wouldn’t want his only child to witness his death. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate for Republicanism. Although primarily an agriculturist, his profession and brief political career shaped him into a man known for his commitment and outspoken views on personal freedom and governance. His support for an agrarian system underpinned nearly all his governmental opinions. His effort to preserve and promote what he saw as the most noble profession influenced his perspectives on sovereignty, the Constitution, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed the United States had a unique opportunity to establish an ideal system due to the absence of native traditions that might constrain the government's founders, enabling the creation of a self-governed society. He was a strong believer in the natural rights of individuals, emphasizing that these rights are interconnected, so if one is denied, all are compromised, reducing the value of those remaining. Thus, these rights should remain beyond governmental reach. He argued that what some termed the "state of nature" allowed those with physical strength and cunning intelligence to thrive, but in a civilization, this should not be the case.

To build this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must be established that considers the inherent good and evil within humans. He was firm in his views on dualistic morality, stating that "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protect private property, enhance agriculture, and discourage capitalism, believing that a government founded on good principles would operate fairly regardless of its leadership, which would inevitably be driven by greed and self-interest. He regarded self-interest as the driving force behind all human actions, considering it only evil when it resulted in societies that thrived at others' expense. A good government was essential to restrain man's natural evil, and even then, it needed close scrutiny to prevent the incorporation of harmful principles.

Like many steadfast Republicans of his era, Taylor advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He desired a very limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers than those explicitly outlined in the Constitution. He recognized that an expansive Federal government would be costly and potentially despotic. However, he believed a simplistic, literal interpretation was dangerous, as it could easily become corrupt without considering the authors' intent. Furthermore, he viewed the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly described the country as a collection of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

I gazed downward, my mind blankly processing the scene before me. With a detached, silent focus, my awareness observed without connecting the subject to any abstract ideas, analyzing the image in front of my eyes. Thoughts drifted into my mind and disappeared almost as quickly as they arrived. My consciousness functioned so smoothly and effortlessly that it felt as if I had no independent thoughts, just an active, fluid experience of what I was observing. 

Once, following advice from an artist I collaborated with, I bought an art instruction book titled The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I had wanted to learn to draw since I was six years old, and this book covers everything from understanding a pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it teaches is to place a square frame around any image the artist wants to study, transforming a complex scene—like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room—into a simple, focused image of just the bowl of fruit on a plain surface. 

At that moment, as I looked down at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally apply that artist's frame. Overwhelmed and in awe, all I could do was stand and marvel. Picasso had his blue period, Monet adored greenery, and Italian Renaissance masters displayed a spectrum of colors. If I aspired to claim my perspective as Artistic, then before me lay the beginnings of my work, the inception of my story, Work in Brown. 

My fingertips touched my chosen tool of artistry, muscles tensing and relaxing as my hand moved through space, my mind's intent taking shape in what could have been my most creative moment. Water swirled, serene and clear. Flakes of matter separated from the whole, carried away to oblivion. Muscles tightened and spasmed more anxiously on the second attempt as my hand struck the toilet handle again. The stubborn brown mass remained immobile, clinging to the toilet bottom like a slug.

With a mop held loosely in my hand, feet spaced a foot apart, and a green tie uncomfortably knotted around my neck, I frowned at the offensive bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the unlucky cleaners at Rite Aid. After a few more flushes and some tranquil, introspective moments, my hand reached for the toilet paper, wrapped it around itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing upright, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the toilet, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey.

Teenagers are losing their lives in car accidents, and several factors contribute to this alarming trend among the youngest drivers in America. According to the National Institutes of Health, one part of the issue is that the teen brain is not yet equipped to handle the dangers of driving. Additionally, lack of experience is a significant factor, leading not only to more fatal crashes but also to an increased rate of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and off-road incidents.  
Teenagers also tend to have worse outcomes when they are driving with their peers—a common occurrence. Research from the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center has demonstrated a link between the age of passengers and the frequency of traffic accidents.  
In an effort to improve teen driver safety, California and other states have implemented temporary provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and prohibit other minors from being passengers.  
However, I believe provisional licenses are merely temporary fixes. The core issue is that, as a group, the youngest drivers are statistically unable to manage the risks and responsibilities effectively. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman even suggests that 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license. His research, reported by USA Today, indicates a prevalent desire among those under 19-20 to engage in risk-taking for the thrill. Therefore, delaying driving until this thrill-seeking tendency diminishes seems logical. Continuing to grant licenses to young teens will likely result in ongoing fatal accidents, with the death toll expected to rise significantly in the coming years. By 2010, the children of Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, adding millions of new teenage drivers to the roads.  
Addressing this issue through legislation would be relatively straightforward. Schools could maintain driver’s education classes to start the learning process, but no one under 18 would be allowed to drive. A provisional permit could be issued before a full license, and a certain number of training hours would still be required. This number could be based on current state requirements (for instance, California mandates 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of adult-supervised practice). Since the concerning statistics for teen drivers emerge nationwide, a uniform, national law would be a sensible and effective way to protect teens across the country.  
The legislation I propose is not a new concept.

This paper explores three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). It begins with a concise definition of the disorder, followed by an explanation of its diagnosis, highlighting common traits or "red flags." The paper concludes with strategies for teachers in mainstream classrooms to support students with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), pertains to how efficiently and effectively the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. Specifically, it involves the perceptual processing of sound information in the CNS and the neurobiological activity that supports this processing, leading to electrophysiological auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Essentially, it is a disorder where the brain struggles to process auditory input accurately. Individuals with CAPD have normal hearing and are not considered "hearing impaired"; rather, the brain region responsible for interpreting sounds, such as distinguishing words or separating conversation from background noise, does not function as it typically should.

The earliest reference to what is now known as CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s, when it was referred to as "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Researchers were studying children with communication disorders at that time. In 1954, the Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children, and by 1961, Kimura had introduced dichotic testing and developed a model to explain the physiology of the central auditory nervous system involved in dichotic perception (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 spurred further research on children with CAPD.

CAPD can present in various ways: individuals may struggle to localize or hear sounds in space, have difficulty distinguishing between different "acoustic events" (sound occurrences), fail to recognize sound patterns, or be unable to detect changes in speech, such as sarcasm indicated by tone shifts. Subsequent sounds might block earlier ones, they might lack the ability to synthesize auditory clues into meaningful information to act upon, and they may struggle to identify the sequence of auditory information (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, patients undergo "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function," which may be administered by "audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using various measures that evaluate auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This process may involve questionnaires, surveys, and observation of how patients respond to specific stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test consistently used with a high success rate for diagnosis, and the disorder's cause remains unknown. Many tests involve presenting the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and asking them to differentiate certain elements, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to these signals.

In choosing to study social work, my goal is to build a career with the Division of Family and Children Services to assist children who have suffered abuse or neglect, and to support families facing difficulties. The values I bring to the field of social work include service, respect, ethical behavior, a commitment to enhancing relationships among people, and a dedication to my own professional development to remain effective in my role. These values are not only essential for social workers but are also personally significant to me.

I have always wanted to help others, though I was initially unsure of the exact career I wanted to pursue. During high school and college, I observed many people avoiding their problems or using less than ideal coping strategies. These experiences led me to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. After graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, still uncertain about my career path, I decided to take a break. One summer day, a friend introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy in her home, who was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had contacted the police about his situation. I went to his parents' home to see if I could assist. I privately shared my concerns with the police, mentioning my recent Psychology degree. They asked me to speak with the parents, as the law offered no immediate solution for the teenager. In conversation, the parents appeared uneasy and made excuses about their son's "manipulative" behavior in seeking outside help for "simple" family disputes. This experience prompted me to seriously consider a career in social work to aid children facing family conflicts.

Another critical value in social work is social justice. As a society, we claim to value individuals and mourn those we lose. However, the societal concept of an "individual" often aligns more with old traditions than true uniqueness. If society truly values individuals, why do we strive to conform? I consider myself an individual and resist limiting myself to fit in with others. Throughout high school and college, I protested social injustice by expressing myself through unconventional hair colors, wearing clothes that reflected my personality, getting additional ear piercings, participating in GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and opposing racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. I am committed to social justice and will continue to stand against social injustices.

This paper examines the Biological and Sociocultural models as they relate to insomnia. The Biological model emphasizes inherited genetic factors and medical health aspects, while the Sociocultural model considers environmental interactions and their relevance to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The review of insomnia explores these models and details each selected piece of research to better elucidate the models. The research and its conclusions are then critiqued to highlight their particular strengths and limitations.

Sleep disorders can be categorized as primary sleep disorders, those related to another mental disorder, or those linked to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, whereas those related to another mental disorder are associated with an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other sleep disorder categories may arise from medical issues or substance use. Dyssomnias encompass Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia involves problems with obtaining or maintaining sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia pertains to difficulties staying awake, both persisting for at least a month. Narcolepsy is characterized by cataplexy and/or automatic REM sleep. Dyssomnias focus on the initiation and maintenance of sleep, whereas Parasomnias relate to sleep disorders with behavioral or physiological anomalies. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders linked to another mental disorder involve sleep challenges due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review primarily considers insomnia and, to some extent, primary sleep disorders in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders centers on genetic, heritable, and physiologically acquired aspects. Hypothalamic neurons containing orexin regulate sleep and wakefulness. Research on mice demonstrated that phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons play a crucial role in sleep/wake states. Activating the GABAA receptor induces sleep-promoting responses, and inhibiting its firing can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) was shown to increase sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These findings suggest that mouse models may be applicable to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or deficiency with this receptor might impair one's ability to achieve sufficient sleep without medication. Socioculturally, if this phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and any alteration to the receptor might naturally disrupt sleep, adversely affecting aspects of life such as education, career, and routine tasks requiring sustained attention.

I have been studying here at University Park for nearly two and a half years, which amounts to four and a half semesters. Navigating the campus can be challenging for many, myself included. During my freshman year, I lived in a dorm room in East Halls, which is about as far east as you can get on campus, aside from the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my dorm in Stuart Hall to classes in distant buildings like Willard, which is near the campus center, could take up to 25 minutes, particularly in the often inclement weather of State College. An alum I spoke with, who isn't much older than me, mentioned that not long ago, East Halls used to be separated from the main campus by large areas of undeveloped land. Now, those areas have been developed with sports fields, large new buildings like the Creamery and a new health services building, and are surrounded by apartments. As the campus continues to grow, getting around becomes increasingly difficult. The best solution for improving mobility on a college campus is the bicycle. However, simply having bikes isn't enough; students need to use them, and the campus must be designed to accommodate cyclists.

I recently spoke with a friend who has started biking again after several years, and he expressed surprise at why he ever stopped. “Bikes are fantastic,” he said, “for a while it wasn’t trendy to ride a bike, but it’s the most practical way to get around.” Besides being beneficial for health, biking is the most efficient mode of transportation. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical effort can take you over 30 miles. Like many other students, I now live off-campus, just as far from the campus center as some dorms. Buying a bike has been my best decision this year. I have classes in the Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my home. Biking can reduce that time to just 5 minutes if I pedal quickly. The only issue is that Pollock Road, the most direct route to the Thomas building from my home, isn’t always easy to navigate, whether you're biking or not. Walking has its merits too, but I’m too busy to walk everywhere. Without my bike, walking would be my sole reliable means of getting to class. Walking to Thomas daily would consume an extra 30-40 minutes of my time each day, totaling over two and a half hours weekly. Adding the time spent walking to other classes, appointments, and more, it’s more time than I can afford to lose.

In "Brave New World," Aldous Huxley critiques the looming dangers posed by technology and the capitalist framework that supports it, by depicting a dystopian society. The inhabitants of this society prioritize community over individuality and are conditioned from birth to seek immediate gratification above everything else. These citizens are mere pawns in a vast scheme, bound to a single ideology as dictated by the World Controller. Analyzing the novel through a Marxist lens reveals Huxley's skepticism about the evolution of these systems. Marxist concepts such as homogeny and reification underscore the idea that Huxley's work comments on the pitfalls of the burgeoning economy of his era.

Capitalism is satirized using the Marxist concept of false consciousness, which asserts that ordinary citizens are kept ignorant of their true economic relationships with other classes, as they focus primarily on personal gain. This is said to result from the ideological control of the proletariat and common workers, a point that is evident in the conditioning seen in "Brave New World." The lower classes, like the Deltas and Gammas, lack genuine free will; their desire to consume and indulge is amplified through hypnopaedia, as orchestrated by the World Controller. Hegemony, where social classes are entirely dominated by a distinct group of individuals, is clearly at play. The lower classes are unaware of their manipulation, literally buying into an ideology that supports capitalism and consumerism. Though the upper classes, like Alphas and Betas, have the potential to recognize this manipulation, few, apart from characters like Bernard, challenge their roles. The interactions among social classes highlight the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In "Brave New World," genuine relationships among different individuals are nonexistent. The novel seems to avoid giving depth to its characters, even among the main ones, possibly suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism strips humanity of free will and expression. Love and strong emotions are absent, with interactions remaining shallow. This is depicted through men's comments on women's physical traits and women's candid remarks about their experiences. Moreover, the complacency of each societal class with their place in the hierarchy reflects the socioeconomic impact of capitalism. Their complete adherence to their roles in the community is indicative of Marxist views on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority as long as they continue to consume and conform.

Nearly four years ago, I attended a course on Islam at CBC. A major topic of debate in the class was whether Islam is an aggressive religion. I believe this issue is even more pertinent now than ever. Reflecting on events since 9/11, I've noticed the mass media shift from a hostile perspective on Islam and extremists to an extreme tolerance for Islam in America. In 2001, it would have seemed unlikely for someone with the name Borac Obama, who has evident Muslim roots in his family, to run for president.

The Prophet's biography fascinates me because, based on my understanding of Muhammad's history, it seems to contradict his personality. From what I've learned, I assumed Muhammad converted people to Islam by force, conquering tribes and compelling them to adopt Islam. However, the biography portrays Muhammad as a misunderstood martyr who humbled himself before others, eventually attracting followers who recognized the 'truth' in his teachings.

Additionally, there are striking similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' attributed to Muhammad. Notably, he is said to have multiplied mutton and milk to feed more than forty men. This narrative style suggests the authors intended to depict Muhammad as a humble prophet who simply lived in truth and performed miracles, without needing to prove anything. I find this problematic because it undermines the miracles and life of Jesus Christ, as if credit for Jesus' life is being claimed through Muhammad.

The biography also contains numerous stories that seem to aim at providing evidence of 'witness' or people converting to Islam 'on their own.' However, many stories are from third-party perspectives, where the author recounts hearing from someone who heard from someone else, and so on. I disliked this approach because, although intended to validate the stories, it made them seem less credible and more dubious.

What disturbs me most about the work is its attempts to glorify Muhammad as a godly figure who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. Yet, historical accounts contradict the portrayal of Muhammad as gentle and humble, and I wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings and beliefs of Jesus during his lifetime were quickly left behind as Christian thought evolved after his death. Observing this historical trajectory broadly, we notice Christianity drifting further from its roots. In today's world, there is a growing awareness and a remarkable progressive trend. While some traditionalists persist and resist thinking beyond their learned teachings, they may not be influential enough to sway the majority. Among Christians, historical understanding will significantly increase in future years. There will be a widespread desire to separate doctrines that were later added to Christianity from the original intentions of its founder. This process may take decades or even centuries, but it seems inevitable: a major shift in Christian history will occur. Christianity will gradually return to its original form, shedding layers of doctrine over time, as though turning back the clock, until only Jesus' initial message from God remains, before other thinkers added their ideas. As this trend spreads across the United States and Europe, leading many to worship as though in Jesus' time, focusing solely on his teachings, the church will remain strong to guide the way. However, because the theological clock will have been reset, the current diversity in Christianity will give way to more uniform beliefs and practices. Across regions and denominations, we will see increasing similarities rather than differences. History is filled with significant reversions. For instance, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, which later embraced Christianity. Similarly, our country has transitioned from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The upcoming significant reversion will occur within Christianity, reversing history to find its original source, and diminishing diversity in the process. This transformation will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus’ words metaphorically rather than literally. So what has happened since Jesus' lifetime? Tracing back in history, we find Judaism, the theological foundation of Christianity. By the time Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, the revelation of divine religion, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the faith. The Jewish people were not unified, dividing into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of ordinary people.

In my view, The Jungle illustrates the inherent greed and self-interest in human nature. People primarily focus on their own well-being and improving their lives, often ignoring those beneath them. This theme is evident throughout the novel, particularly in the actions of the factory owners and managers. Their sole aim is to expand and enhance their businesses, showing no concern for those affected by their pursuits. Upton Sinclair's narrative highlights this through vivid imagery: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair illustrates the environmental and social damage caused by pollution, showing the owners' disregard for the harm to people and animals. They are indifferent to the smoke and waste pollution from the factories and surrounding animal pens. 

Moreover, the owners and managers have little regard for the workers who enrich them. They exploit their workforce to maximize profits, creating an environment rife with jealousy and animosity, devoid of loyalty or decency. Employees are subjected to grueling hours and can be laid off en masse without notice, compensation, or assistance in finding new employment. During the period depicted in The Jungle, labor laws and worker protections were virtually non-existent, allowing employers to impose harsh conditions and demand faster work. Although the book doesn't explicitly state it, workers living and laboring in Packingtown were expected to endure the appalling conditions at work and in their communities. There were no agencies to support or inform workers, and while unions existed, they often exploited workers further. The employees were so poorly treated and trapped in the system that they resembled slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

"Dream-Land" is one of Edgar Allan Poe's poems that he regarded highly. In this poem, Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott links to Virgil. Virgil mentioned this term referring to an island north of Britain, considered by the Greeks as the boundary of the known world. While Virgil indeed used the term, there's a more contemporary influence worth noting. Poe had a keen interest in German authors. This interest is significant as it highlights Poe’s familiarity with Goethe’s work. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," notes the similarity between their poems, suggesting Poe was imitating Goethe. 

The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned author of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's death. In the second part of "Faust," there is a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem tells of a king whose wife dies after gifting him a goblet. Grieving, the king drinks heavily and mourns his lost queen. Eventually, he decides to die, giving his possessions to his children except for the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The king’s demeanor and his portrayal in "Dream-Land" share similarities, perhaps reflecting Poe's own struggles with loss and drinking. "Faust" was also adapted into a romantic drama by H.P. Grattan in 1842, shortly before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum." 

Poe mentions Thule twice in his collected works. He refers to "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and uses it twice as a framing device in "Dream-Land." "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as complementary. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes Thule as dark and lonely, haunted by deceased friends, and perceives a colorless, shadowy world. These themes echo Goethe's "The King of Thulé," where the king mourns his wife, feels isolated, and loses his will to rule or live. The poem feels as though the speaker walks into Goethe’s work. 

Goethe was a prominent author whom Poe would have known, not only due to his admiration for Tennyson. Poe expressed his respect for Tennyson, and this connection, along with the many reproductions of Goethe’s work after its initial publication, would have exposed Poe to Goethe’s influence.

Under California law, can a customer who was injured after slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store receive punitive damages if it can be shown that the store manager acted with malice? This might be argued if the manager was informed twice about the spill but delayed cleaning it for half an hour due to having dinner. A judge is unlikely to immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s claim for punitive damages. To justify such a claim, the plaintiff needs to provide evidence that the defendant acted with a willful and conscious disregard for the likely harm their actions could cause, as well as prove that the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known about the potential harm of leaving a spill unattended, especially since there had been several slip-and-fall incidents at D&D in the months before her accident. Despite this, Martin did not address the spill. Although Palmer’s argument that Martin’s behavior was despicable is less convincing, it remains reasonable given that six similar incidents occurred in 2009 and Martin still did not take necessary safety measures.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin, on his dinner break, said he didn’t have time for customer complaints. At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Martin of the spill, and his response was the same. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill and suffered a serious back injury. Before Palmer’s accident, five slip-and-fall incidents were reported at D&D in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages due to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can obtain punitive damages for breaching a non-contractual obligation if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice," according to Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or if not intended, the conduct must be "despicable" and done with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Courts have deemed conduct malicious when done with a conscious disregard for the plaintiff’s rights, especially when the defendant was aware of the probable dangerous consequences and willfully failed to prevent them, as noted in Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She always felt an unfulfilled longing, a need that started around the age of 14 as she entered her teenage years. Even at 17, she still experienced this yearning, realizing it was for someone rather than something. Despite this realization, she found herself uninterested in boys. Though some had tried, often awkwardly, to win her over, none captured her interest. She frequently pondered why she felt this way, considering various theories over the years but never finding a satisfactory explanation. She continued to live her life, persistently questioning her desires.

Most days at home were peaceful, as her parents were calm, never quarreling with each other and rarely with her. The only disagreements arose from her expression of independence and free spirit. Despite having calm parents, she balanced their tranquility with her vibrant and fun personality, making her both likable and genuinely nice.

However, today was different. As she moved through the house, seeking inspiration, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, her mother's beautiful voice. Rushing in, panic set in as she frantically asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mother lay on the floor, clearly in pain, repeatedly murmuring "Ow" in short breaths. Quickly, she knelt beside her mother to help. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital," her mother gasped. Her daughter recognized the urgency in her voice. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Following her mother's directions, she felt thankful for the strength she gained from her classes. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back, and drove to the hospital.

Arriving at the hospital, she was too focused on her mother to notice the usual scents of disinfectant and fear. She swiftly carried her injured mother inside, urgently calling for medical assistance. Several concerned staff members gathered, quickly placing her mother on a rolling bed and taking her for immediate care, leaving her daughter to wait anxiously.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while trying to retrieve a vase from the highest cabinet.

This research aimed to demonstrate that following a Mediterranean Diet, indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked to a decreased risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and mortality due to stroke. The aMed diet is a variation of the Mediterranean Diet, emphasizing increased consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (as opposed to saturated fats), and fish, while minimizing intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have shown a negative correlation between adherence to a Mediterranean Diet and the risk of overall and cardiovascular mortality, with an intervention trial revealing that the Mediterranean Diet is more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio in obese individuals. However, prior studies did not specifically address stroke or stroke-related mortality.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, who had no history of cardiovascular disease or diabetes and were part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. The authors calculated an aMed diet score six times between 1984 and 2004 using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) to evaluate nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of participants remained in the study for the entire 20-year period. The FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were corroborated through medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. In cases lacking records, incidents were deemed "probable" and included, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions classified this way. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, and leisure-time physical activity was recorded starting in 1986.

To minimize random individual variation and better reflect long-term dietary habits, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated by averaging scores from two previous years. Adjustments were made for confounding factors, including age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

The study used Cox proportional-hazard modeling to evaluate the relationship between the aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean Diet, reflected in a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a reduced risk of developing CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, there were 2,391 new cases of CHD, 1,763 new cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combining fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile, with a relative risk (RR) of 0.71.

The sign reads, "Hitler is alive in Burma," held by Ellen Page, the leading actress from Juno, as she stands alone on a street corner with the message scrawled in Sharpie on a piece of cardboard. Burma, or Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation governed by a repressive military junta that seized power through a coup in 1962. In 2007, Burma witnessed its first public demonstrations in a decade, known as "The Saffron Revolution," led predominantly by Burmese monks, named after the color of their robes. Initially, the Burmese government reluctantly permitted the monks to gather peacefully, but the situation soon escalated into a violent confrontation between the monks and the military, with the military raiding monasteries nationwide. Foreign journalists were detained and jailed, and Japanese photojournalist Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, during a street protest. The official death toll is recorded at 13, but Colonel Hla Win, an army defector, claimed, “Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand.”

These occurrences are not new. Governments have long sought to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control over their citizens. Roman emperors declared themselves divine rulers with total authority over their societies. Japanese emperors are considered deities, believed to lead their people to prosperity. Meanwhile, President George W. Bush reportedly has regular conference calls with Ted Haggard, head of Stupid People Worldwide, a group associated with the Republican Party.

Historically, notable examples of such actions include the Tiananmen Square protests on June 4, 1989, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students protested against the government’s authoritarian rule. The death toll from this event varies widely, with Chinese government reports claiming 200-300 deaths, while the Chinese Red Cross reported between 2,000 and 3,000 deaths. Another instance is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militias, supported by the Rwandan government, systematically killed Tutsis and political moderates. Additionally, Hitler’s 'Third Reich' represents a period marked by the genocide of Jews across several years and countries.

Duke Ellington's lasting influence in jazz largely stems from his long career and his creative ability to shape his orchestra. While his piano presence is often understated in many of the works chosen for this assignment, as a composer, Ellington excelled in crafting intricate pieces that highlighted the unique talents of his band members. He designed frameworks that allowed soloists to improvise freely and composed tightly orchestrated sections that emphasized the distinctive styles of his musicians to bring out musical concepts. This approach also underscored the overall tone of the orchestra, creating cohesive and original sounds tailored to each composition. Ellington's skill in understanding both the individual sound of his players and how they blended in a growing ensemble enabled him to create some of the most innovative and remarkable works in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary, when discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, refers to "Creole Love Call" as an early example of his use of voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This piece illustrates Ellington's ability to add texture and color without relying on lyrics and showcases his talent for complementing his soloists' styles, evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues composition consists of six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Features a call and response between voice and reeds, starting with a smooth melodic voice that turns rougher towards the end.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo elaborates on the melody, highlighting several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register is supported by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: The full band mirrors the first chorus with a call and response between brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus has the reeds initiating the call and response in a high register, supported by syncopated stop-time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: Returns to the structure of the first chorus, with a call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice uses the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Concludes with a brief vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to enhance tone color in this piece exemplifies a stylistic trait that is pervasive in his work. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington combines tight orchestration with an ear for tone color. A call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing integrates the vocal qualities of Miley’s playing with the instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice, creating a rich, complementary sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" builds on these ideas, as Ellington effectively utilizes Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a staple in his orchestra, to introduce the melody with a muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the ways they do? Are there specific limitations or constraints that shape the course of evolutionary change? Although D’Arcy Thompson in 1917 remarked that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," this observation remains relevant today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been employed to explore general aspects of mollusk shell formation, both in the context of individual development and evolutionary history (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research investigates how mathematical modeling of changes during development and evolution in Prunum, coupled with experimental studies, can clarify the mechanisms that determine the direction and extent of evolutionary-developmental change. We utilized X-ray images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters that can be used to model both theoretical and actual shell shapes. These parameters were inputted into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We created models of theoretical shell shapes to explore the limits of possible morphological changes in Prunum. These findings are being integrated with experimental and descriptive research to gain a deeper understanding of major evolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be considered as a structure that forms a tube, revolving over time through 360 degrees of space. These revolutions, or turns of a coiled shell, are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the shell's central column, known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls expand can differ, and a continuous line, called a suture, separates each whorl. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one, known as the body whorl. The spire includes all whorls except the last. The spire's tip is the apex, while the opposite end is the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upward.)

A method for counting whorls is described below. First, view the shell from the apical perspective and identify where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn, dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a sequence of apertures moving through time and space as the animal builds its shell. It is possible to trace the aperture's path using the coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture, as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be represented graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical formulation is established, it becomes possible to alter parameters and modify the mollusk's shell formation.

For the past decade, Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have shown little change. Although the nation is progressing towards achieving many Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation, the advancements in child and maternal health fall significantly short of the targets set for 2015. The underlying causes of these deficiencies, which will be elaborated upon below, indicate a necessity to enhance the health system instead of solely concentrating on specific program interventions.

Indonesia has seen an increase in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, reaching 72%. However, this statistic still includes traditional workers, like midwives, who cannot perform medical procedures in complicated pregnancies, contributing to the high rate of maternal deaths from hemorrhage. Thus, the progress in this area is somewhat deceptive, and substantial improvements are still required. Moreover, there has been a reduction in the percentage of children under five with diarrhea being treated by healthcare professionals. Although data on postnatal care is not comprehensive, it is evident that this is another area of concern, with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean-section rates remain lower than expected, around 4%. These rates highlight another issue: the disparity in healthcare access. While urban areas have a c-section rate of 7%, rural areas only have a rate of 2%, illustrating the inequitable distribution of healthcare services. Additionally, there is a 27% gap in healthcare service usage between the poorest and richest segments of the population, indicating that the poor face significant barriers to accessing healthcare, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

In considering steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, a fundamental question arises: how can the service gap be most effectively addressed? Should Indonesia focus on specific program interventions or strengthen the entire health system without concentrating exclusively on pre and postnatal care? While program-specific solutions offer clear, manageable goals and typically yield quicker results, they also have downsides. One major issue is that heavy investment in a particular health sector area can divert funds from other areas, drawing human resources towards the better-funded sector, as seen with international funding for HIV/AIDS impacting the family planning sector. Furthermore, running multiple concurrent programs for one area can lead to service duplication and lack of coordination, resulting in increased paperwork for supplies and funding.

The classification of popular music has expanded significantly over the last century, now encompassing so many genres that it's challenging to list them all comprehensively. Adding to this complexity, nearly every genre—like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—has generated numerous sub-genres and even more specific sub-sub-genres. Among these, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has arguably become one of the most varied and expressive forms of popular music over the past 40 years. It is considered expressive because it covers a broad spectrum of emotions, albeit generally on the darker side. Its diversity stems from the early realization of its inherent flexibility, which musicians quickly leveraged to create their own sub-genres, leading to further sub-sub-genres, a trend that continues today.

Currently, the heavy metal scene has evolved to such an extent that the sheer number of niche groups makes it challenging to define what heavy metal truly is. It has absorbed a wide array of themes from other genres, yet it originated from a specific point. To properly comprehend the metal music prevalent today, one must first grasp what the metal movement represents and why it is considered a movement rather than just a genre.

In many respects, metal is a movement characterized by darkness. It can be described as "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more intensity, more theatricality. It moves away from primitivism towards technical skill; members of metal bands are adept musicians, which is evident in their music. Additionally, metal is a movement significantly influenced by drugs, particularly following the psychedelic drug surge of the mid-70s, which led people to create extraordinary, otherworldly records, using drugs as inspiration. Metal's dark, visceral qualities were a novel addition to the music scene, contrasting with the lighter themes in much of popular music. Moreover, later generations of metal drew inspiration from the dark, visceral elements prevalent in the Romantic Era. Lyrics from songs like "Helter Skelter" by the Beatles highlight the darkness integral to this movement.

These lyrics from "Helter Skelter" showcase the Beatles' darker side, reflecting the highs and lows associated with drugs. Some consider it among the first Heavy Metal songs, created in response to a similarly heavy and dark Rolling Stones song. The Beatles aimed to demonstrate that they could be as intense as the Stones, thus including the track on "The White Album."

Several decades prior to the emergence of Surrealist artists with their dream-inspired creations, Henri Rousseau was meticulously forming his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. His 1910 painting, The Dream, not only portrays a woman marveling at the extraordinary landscape she encounters in a dream, but it also symbolizes Rousseau’s personal aspirations and ambitions as an artist. From the onset of his career, Rousseau yearned for recognition, acceptance, and acclaim from fellow artists and art enthusiasts, yet he faced a challenging internal conflict in pursuit of this goal. The Dream encapsulates Rousseau's persistent internal struggle throughout his career: whether to adhere to or imitate certain artistic styles to gain acceptance in the esteemed art world he greatly admired, or to embrace his creative independence and distinctiveness, forging his own path as he progressed.

Before delving into an analysis of The Dream through this lens, it is essential to be acquainted with Rousseau’s background. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France, Rousseau was the son of a tinsmith and hardware dealer who "enjoyed bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). He lacked formal artistic education and worked for the municipal toll service in France until the age of forty, although he was erroneously nicknamed a customs inspector, or douanier (Shattuck 46). The loss of his first wife, Clémence, after the deaths of their eight infant children, left Rousseau with a daughter named Julia and profound sorrow (Shattuck 49). Seeking solace and a fresh start, he turned to painting as a refuge. Unlike his contemporaries, who often romanticized peasants in their art, Rousseau was fundamentally a folk painter who embodied the aspirations and dreams of an average person from his social background.

Rousseau’s intense desire for acceptance in the art world is somewhat understandable in context: as noted, he was self-taught in formal painting techniques and commenced his artistic career later in life, while competing with numerous other skilled and more renowned modern artists. Despite years of work, it was not until the same period that Matisse began establishing his reputation as an artist that Rousseau started to gain proper recognition for his art. In the book Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon notes that although Rousseau and Matisse were rivals in the art scene, they differed not only in style and subject matter but also in their motivations for painting: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many prominent thinkers have suggested a deep relationship between ethics and aesthetics, as well as truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this connection. As John Keats expresses in "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we understand in life comes through education or experience. Yet, as Keats implies, we seem to grasp ethics and aesthetics naturally, without the need for formal teaching. Both fields strive to describe rather than dictate. Our exploration of morality and beauty largely involves explaining why a work of art or literature is beautiful or why an action is moral, rather than offering a set of rules for evaluating or creating good art or ethical behavior.

Furthermore, critiques of art or morals never fully capture the essence of what is good or beautiful. For instance, discussions about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on aspects like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural significance, but these do not truly explain why it is considered great art. When asked about a favorite piece of art or literature, people often say, "There's just something about it," before providing a more detailed or analytical explanation. I believe that both art and morals cannot be entirely reduced to descriptions of their attributes. As Flannery O'Connor states, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how thoroughly we describe the features of a literary work, there remains a transcendent quality. I think ethics shares this same characteristic. Wittgenstein noted, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I propose that this "something," this indescribable essence, is the most compelling aspect of art and morality, and that the transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics connects them.

I believe morality and art are closely linked because we experience both most profoundly at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They affect us in a way that can be felt but not fully explained. This connection is even more pronounced in the art of literature. As McKean observes, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Modern Germany is seen as a powerful and unified nation, showcasing a unique cultural blend stretching from the Alps' shadows in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel.
